The obvious differences between the signals recorded from walking and running is that the running linear acceleration data is slightly larger than that of the walk linear acceleration data considering all linear acceleration components.

The transition times can be seen at the beginning and end of the recordings as have a slightly lower linear acceleration considering all components, seen quite clearly at the beginning of the run recording. And seen slightly (but less obviously) at the start of the walk recording and the end of the run and walk recordings. This is not as obvious for the start of the walk recording and the end of the run and walk recordings because I tried starting running/walking before starting the recording and finishing my running/walking after completing the recording.

In [83]:
#sklearn.model_selection.RepeatedKFold
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import RepeatedKFold
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score

M = RandomForestClassifier()
rkf = RepeatedKFold(n_splits = 10, n_repeats = 10, random_state = 191856638)
auc = list()
X_rf =  X[select.relevant_features]

for train_index, test_index in rkf.split(X_rf):
    x_train = X_rf.iloc[train_index]
    x_test = X_rf.iloc[test_index]
    
    x_pred = M.fit(x_train,target[train_index])
    y_pred = x_pred.predict(x_test)
    
    y = target[test_index].values
    
    auc.append(roc_auc_score(y,y_pred))

print(sum(auc)/len(auc))

1.0

Model is 100% effective at distinguishing between running and walking signals.

The machine learning model does not know if the costs are different for missclassifications, it assumes costs are identical. Hence a cost of the model could be False Negatives where a person is running slowly but are classified as walking, indiciating health problems potentially which could discourage users of the hypothetical health application. However False Positives wouldn't be as bad of a missclassification as fast walkers being missclassified as runners wouldn't have a negative effect on the user.

This would change the decision model as we would try to minimize the False Negative rate to lead to better health recommendations for the user using the hypothetical health application. So that we could correctly identify slow runners and allow them to feel content about their health by being correctly classified and not discouraged by being misclassified.
